{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hooloovoo_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280656823/1920101201/0148.xml":{"full_text":"PINEY BRANCH HITS\nHIGHER GAS RATES\nOpposition Voted by Citizens.\nApprove Use of $4,000,000\nSurplus.\nOpposition to the proposed increase\nin gas rates for Washington was\nvoted last night by the Piney Branch\nCitizens' Association, at its monthly\nmeeting. The association also approved\nthe proposal that the $4,000,000\nof surplus District revenues now lying\nidle in the federal Treasury be used\nto acquire much needed school buildings\nfor the* National Capital.\nOn a motion presented by George A.\nFinch, the association voted that the\nproposed increase in gas rates, which\nwould prive the company 8 per cent on\nits capital investment, \"was unconscionable.\"\nAfter stating that the peak for high\nprices had been passed, Mr. Finch\nsaid that if there was any particular\nclass in the city trying to keep prices\nup. it was the duty of all citizens to\nget together and see that they come\ndown.\nHe then added a second clause to\nthe resolution, in whiturTne gas company\nwas asked to consider seriously\ngoing back to 95-cent gas from the\npresent $1.25. which he claimed was\na war price pure and simple.\nThe speaker, who is one of the\nPiney Branch Association's delegates\nto the Federation of Citizens* Associations.\nthen denied charges that the\nfederation wasted time and was a\nuseless organization.\n\"The committees of the federation,\nespecially the public utilities committee.\"\nhe said, \"do an enormous\namount of work for the good of the\ncommunity, work worth to any business\nman a salary of $15,000 a year,\nyet it all is gratuitous.\n\"It is impossible to figure in dollars\nand cents just what their work is\nworth. In the recent controversy with\nthe milk dealers' association, for instance,\nit was entirely due to the\nwork of the federation that 1 cent a\ngallon was saved on this commodity,\nwhich meant a total saving to the\ncitizens of the District of $250,000.\"\nAfter notifying the association that\nthe federation was in need of funds to\ndefray ordinary expenses, and deserved\nthe help and support of its\nconstituent bodies, it was voted to\nsuggest to the federation that the\nPiney Branch association would be\namenable to a 5-cent per capita tax.\nBetter Policing Discussed.\nEdgar B. Henderson presided, and\nafter a vote of congratulation had been\nextended to Mr. and Mrs. J. Wallace\nAllen for their behavior when recently\nattacked by a burglar in their\nhouse, the question of better police\nprotection for the Piney Branch section\nof the city was gone into at\ngreat length.\nIt was finally voted to propose to\nthe Commissioners that the tenth precinct\nbe divided, it being pointed out\nthat the present boundary lines of\nthat precinct were the longest in the\ncity if not in the United States.\nChairman T. A. Bradford of the\npublic service committee, reported\nthat the association's plea for cheaper\ncarfare for school children was being\nheld up due to the lack of authority\nof either the street car companies or\nthe Public Utilities Commission to\nact. Letters from each were read explaining\nthe situation.\nThe association also renewed its\nprevious action in regard to the congested\nstreet car trackage in the center\nof the city, and voted to have the\nfederation urge necessary improvements.\nIt also renewed its advocacy\nof merging the street car lines, as\npreviously voted on.\nA motion was carried whereby the\nSociety for Tuberculosis be urged to\nerect the proposed school for tubercular\nchildren away from the Tuberculosis\nHospital, and it also was resolved\nthat steps be taken for the ultimate\nremoval of the hospital itself\nfrom that section of the city.\nStreet Grades Asked.\nA resolution was adopted requesting\nthe Commissioners to grade streets\nthrough the reservation surrounded\nby 13th, Upshur. Spring road, Allison\nand Colorado avenue, and to note the\nassociation's protest against the reported\nsuggestion that the stables of\nthe District street cleaning department\nbe erected on the reservation.\nA motion was carried urging that\nthe Commissioners place warning signals\non streets in the vicinity of the\nWest School building.\nASSIGNED TO CAMP DIX.\nCol. Francis E. Lacy, jr., infantry,\nhas been relieved from duty with the\nwar plans division, general staff, this\ncity, and assigned to the 16th Infantry\nat Camp Dix. N. J.\n\"The Standard\nof Its Field\"\nElectric\nI Washer\n?mechanically perfect\n?simple to operate\n?easily cleaned witho\nremoving the cylinder.\nTTH-E THOR is the stai\narc! by which\ni!ll others are iudfred. Th\nH B\nvalues are told by comp\nH ing them with it.\nFor fourteen years 1\nThor has been the leadei\nQ ing machine field. Its i\ncomplete satisfaction a\nextends fro^i coast to c\nmillion satisfied users r\nI J 1 A PUTS A THOR lb\nIIB iiAi.wn: iv smm\nM. V MONTI\nVisit the nearest Thor\nour store?as you wish,\ntake the same pride in si\nThor that we take in telli\nI Everything k I Al*\nf?rthe NAI\nMotorist\n13\nOFFICERS ELECT\nASSUME\nTakoma Park Association\nOpposes Gas Rate Raise;\nAsks for High School.\nIn the presence of the largest atj\ntendance in the history of the organizaI\ntion the newly elected officers of the\nj Takoma Park Citizens' Association took\nI charge of the business last night at a\nmeeting held in the Takoma Public Li1\nbrary. ]n a brief address President\nJesse C. Suter outlined the work of the\nassociation for the ensuing year, and\n'laid particular stress upon the principal\nmatters in which the members should\ni give full support.\ni The association declared opposition to\n{any increase in the present gas rate\nj and will insist on a reduction of the\nI nrfsrnt rate to 95 cents when the hear\n1 ing is held before the Tublic 1/tilities\n(Commission next Monday. According to\n(information presented, in the event the\n1 request for an increase is not granted\nI the old rate automatically goes into efi\nfeet.\nV*len for High School.\nI The erection of a northern high school\non the site of the present hospital between\nI'pshur and Allison, 13th streets\nand Iowa avenue, was discussed and the\nI school committee directed to start the\nI movement in order to relieve the con]\n(tested condition of the high schools,\nj The committee will co-operate with the\nvarious committees which will be appointed\nin the third division.\nA committee composed of Maj. D. S,\nFletcher, chairman, of the association:\nillrs. L. It. Kurdette of the Civic Study\nit'lub and C. C. Carroll of the Horticul'\ntural Club was appointed to confer with\nthe officials of the Washington I'ublic\nLibrary with a view to continuing the\nI present hours of the Takoma Library\nwithout the curtailment proposed due to\nlack of appropriation of funds by Coni\ngross at the last session.\nThe association indorsed the request\nnf thf> PVrlorat ion of Assn\niciation, to co-operate and support the\n1 intensive rat extermination campaign\njnow being: conducted in this city. The\nhouseholders of the suburb were re'\nquested to communicate with the\nDistrict health department or bureau\nof biological survey. Department of\nAgriculture, if troubled with rats or\nmice.\nMrs. Angus A. Lamond was elected\nsecond vice president. The following\nwere re-elected to membership: H. L.\nBudd. William C. Beck, Miss Nellie R.\nMacFarlnn. Mrs. F. W. Pearce, Robert\n1,. Waters, H. K. Hobart and James\nG. Greene.\nStanding Committees.\nThe following standing committees\nwere announced by President Suter\nfor the ensuing year:\nFire and police?Preston C. King,\nchairman, M. C. Betts, Fred L. Harries.\nStreets and lights?H. R. Thorntorb\nchairman, E F. Ramsey, jr.; Dr. D. N.\nShoemaker. Thomas E. Holmes. Samuel\nScrivener.\nRegislation?J. Bond Smith, chairjman;\nJohn Humpnrey, Airs. Angus A.\nI i.smnnd sr E. E. Reynolds, Otto\nVeerhoff.\nMembership?V. L. Pearce, chairman:\nW. C. Irev, vice chairman; Samuel\nC. Redman, Clau