.\nBliss.\nPostal facilities?It. V. Ferner,\nchairman: Charles Fietz.\nHorticultural?-C. C. Carroll, chairman:\nDr. D. N. Shoemaker, II. B. Hendrick,\nL. C. Corbett.\nIn Charge of Entertainment.\nEntertainment?Mrs. Otto Veerhoff.\nchairman; Fred L. Harries, vice chairman;\nAlbert Browning, James W.\nDyre, W. S. Diffenbaugh, Mrs. H. C.\nGore, Mrs. H. W. Whitaker, Mrs. W.\nH. H. Smith, Mrs. James L. Wilmeth.\nSchool gardens?Dr. D. N. Shoemaker.\nchairman: W. T. Simmons. II.\nW. Whitaker, Prof. W. A. Orton.\nBusiness interests?H. K. Hobart.\nchairman: Samuel C. Redman, J. M.\nBigelow.\nFinance and audit?W. Preston Gibson,\nchairman.\nCommunity interests?James.L. Wilmeth,\nchairman; Le Blonde Burdette.\nvice chairman; Rev. C. M. Young, Rev.\nThnmas C. Clark. Mrs. Mary L. White,\nMrs. J. H. Arnold, \\V. G. i'latt.\nThe president will appoint a special\ncommittee to' revise the present constitution\nof the association.\nTEN SHIPS SOLD.\nTen Rovernment-owned vessels, aggregating\n25.G6G deadweight tons,\nhave been sold for $2,S36,110, it was\nannounced last night by the Whipping\nBoard. Six lake type steamers, totaling\n18.5S9 ions, sold for $75,000 each\nand four cargo vessels, totaling 11,977\ntons, brought I2.3S6.110.\nChairman Benson said the hoard had\nrejected all bids received last week\nfor the wooden fleet of 285 vessels.\nIV\n407 7th St.\nore. Honrs. Dally. ShIO a.m. to 8 p.m.\nIn 19. Dr. J. K. Frelot, Prop.\nman, Modern Electric Shop,\nixket, 1411 TT St. N.W.\nteman, John J. Odenwald,\nSt. N.K. nnnA TT Ci V TTT\nn. ofc.\nPST* Premier Service Co.,\n70* 10th St. N.W.\nN.W. Harry I. Scharr,\nrtric Co.. 711 13th St. N.W.\nIt. N.W. N. D. Staughton,\niarko, 22* Holly Ave..\nAve. N.W. Takoma Park,\nilliflower, Tuberville Harding,\nit. N.W. 709 12th St. N.W.\nrtin Co.. Washington Electric Co.,\nN.W. 21 H St. N.W.\ni Bro? White A Boyer.\nt, N.W. 812 13th St. N.W.\nnpkins, Suburban Electrio Co.,\nN.W. Bockville- Md.,\nJong*, Watkins A Washington,\n-oad N.W. Alexandria, Va