' appointments to all\nranking posts in the organization.\nRev. Brother D. Edward, president,\nhas announced.\nTheir names follow: First sergeants,\nFleming Peak, Ernest Keasier, Joseph\nWIIIIW, V iU I'JS DClf,CMIlS,\n(Jeorgro Finnin, Michael Venditti,\nHarry Hagrnn, Angrustus Bartels,\nFraivis It. Shea, William Shanahan,\nMorriss McGrejror, John J. Ryan. John\nJfg*swanfc *r f$~:- -drSS.\nwnniiM nillP?w\nii'ii't1 i\" ??i Jm Canadian Factory\n73 St. Alexander Si\nMontreal, Quebec\n\nMutt. (0opn\nIbsT STANbl f\n-r?S r-J IT'S ftbL RIGHT, 1\n3l* L SIR'. COMING, j\"\nember'S I I SIR'. ti\nOFF? wW.\nje wow. J I\nFIMC'. 1 v \"i\nLuminous Cable\nAs Fog Ship Guide,\nNewest Discovery\nPARIS, October 12.?Te?t* of a\nj luminous cable by which steam;\nj j or* may enter and leave port\nduring; heavy have been\nattended by Admiral Fournier\nand the minisi<>r of the navy,\nwho have reported them to have\nbeen entirely successful.\nIt has been drilled to install\none of these rabies in the principal\nFrench ports, and the\nMatin cuiys the i>laeine of one\nacross the Pn^liMh channel is\nl?einsr considered.\nLyons, Lawrence O'Brien, Albert\nMurphy, Robert Mahoraey, and corporals,\nJohn McGinn ess, Reginald\ni j Nalley, Edward Sullivan, Kdward\nI Keefe, Hubert Beall, George Manpran\nI NTorris Wooldrid^e, Le Roy Ttaftery\nFrancis Werle, Noel McDonnell\nj Thomas Fen ton, Joseph Bonner, James\ni Grant and Daniel J, Joseph.\n'I'i'S'I 'n'lTrio r\nT?-'o a nillal\no a vjixxv\nlonger handle s\nGillette in pri\nI ~i though you m:\nand balance t\nmen, especial]\nhands, say thi\n~^jjl No Stroppin\nr\" I dealer show y<\nNew Tork London Madrid J\nt. Chicago Puis Brnaaela C\nSan Francisco Milan Copenhagen X\nU II-..Ul.nmi\night, 1920, by H. C. Fisher. Trade mark\nregistered U. S. Pat. Off.)\n*BL{ MANY\nigs- MXJTTI THere^s I r^o _\nA TeRRlBLE I N^3\nL=. I DftAU&Wr IN J ///f0'\nTV^\no?i n*i.\"mi M. c n*>)\nW\nSHIPPING BOARD ACTIVE.\n\nBottoms Carried 20,615.402 Tons\nin a Year.\nNEW YOI'.K, October 12.?Vessels\nof the United States Shipping Board\ncarried 13,379.2.14 tons of export merchandise\nand 7,236.16S tons of imports\n'during the fiscal year ended June 30\nI last, according to a statement of\nI Shipping Board activities made public\nj here today. The cargo carried, the\nj report states, constituted ;h> pi r cent\n(of the country's export business and\n27 per cent of the imports, the percentages\nbeing fixed on the return\nof the total foreign commerce of th>United\nStates for the fiscal year.\nThe business of the Shipping Board\nwas handled through forty-nine\nAmerican ports, New York ranking\nfirst with 23.2 per cent'of the exports\nI and 36.6 per cent of the imports, or\n127.9 per cent of the total business.\nBaltimore and Philadelphia ranked\nsecond, each with 10 per cent, and New\nI j Orleans third, with 7.6 per cent.\n1 The north Atlantic district, inelud.\ning eleven ports from Baltimore\nnorth, handled nearly 4S per cent of\nthe export business and f.S per cent\ni of the imports; the south Atlantic\ndistrict handled 19 per cent of the\nMusitjmssBm ssaaRBBsss\ntte with a\nmd heavier\ninciple all the way through,\nay find a little more poise\no the Big Fellow some\nly those with large size\n2y do.\ng?No Honing. Have a\ndu the Big Fellow.\n.mztardaa Sydaey Calcutta Hiod\nmrrrn Skufktl Constantinople Toky\nInenot Ail** Biipion Port Elizabeth\ni i\n\n\nBy BUD FISHER.\ns:\" ^ifsr\n'->1. .^-w5?SI i \\-l,; I\nj\ncombined exports and imports, and\nthe' gulf district 16.7 per cent. Tin- i\nPacific division handled 11 per cent.\nExports were forwarded to twenty\nforeign trade regions, nineteen of\nwhich returned imports. Iceland being\nthe exception. Included among\nthe imports handled were 1,720.73.*;\ntons of crude petroleum, constituting\n24 per cent of the total import\nbusiness.\nPANEL OF TALESWOMEN.\nJury Summoned at Newark, N. J\nin Dressmaker's Dispute.\nNEWARK. N. J. October 12.?Worn 'on.\nnewly enfranchised in this state.\ntake their duties as jurors more sen jously\nthan do men. John E. (lallagher\nsergeant-at-arms of the Orange dis\ni trict court, declared today after sen\ning subpoenas on the state's firs\npanel of taleswomon.\nOut of twelve women summoned\nonly one obj'-cted to serving, and sin\nconsented when assured that she was\nnot too young.\nThe women will sit tomorrow in\n'suit involving a dispute between\ndressmaker and a pattern mapufaciu\ni irig company.\nIHBBflgZy TC\nEjwhtq^ TT\ni","height":"29884","width":"22712"}}
